Boil a large #pot{} of water with @salt{1/4%tsp} for your rice. Once the water
is rapidly boiling add the @Basmati Rice{1}. Cook for around ~{25%minutes} or
until soft enough to eat. Drain the rice and place back in the pot with a
cloth over it, until you are ready to eat.

Meanwhile, chop the @British Chicken Thighs{4} into bite-sized chunks. Peel and
finely dice half the @Red Onion{1/2}(peeled and finely diced) and the
@Garlic Cloves{2}(peeled and finely diced). Slice the @Red Chilli{1} in half and
dice as much as you want for your curry.

> The spice mix is already slightly hot so go careful if you like it mild.

Chop the ends off your @Green Beans{1} and cut them in half.

Using the edge of a #spoon{} peel the skin from the @Ginger{1}. Dice the
ginger very finely.

Heat @oil{1/2%tbsp} in a #non-stick frying pan{} on high heat. Toss the chicken
pieces in a #bowl{} with the @Cornflour{1.5} and a good pinch of @salt{pinch}
and @ground black pepper{}. Once the oil is really hot, gently add the chicken
into the pan (it'll sputter a bit). Cook for a few mins until golden brown then
remove from the pan.

Turn the heat down to medium-low and add another @oil{1/2%tbsp}. Add the onion,
garlic, chilli and ginger and cook gently for ~{5%minutes}.

> Make sure you do not burn the ingredients - if they are getting too hot add
> 1 tbsp of cold water and turn the heat down.

Add the @Tandoori Paste{1} to the onion mix and cook for a further ~{1%minute}.
Next add the @Chopped Tomatoes{1}(tinned) with @?sugar{1/4%tsp} (if you have some)
and @salt{1/4%tsp}. Add the chicken back into the pan. Turn the heat to low
and let the mixture gently bubble until slightly thicker.

Once the sauce has thickened, add two-thirds of the @Greek Style Natural Yoghurt{1}
along with your green beans. Stir and leave to bubble gently for ~{5%minutes}.

Serve the curry with your rice and a drizzle of the remaining yoghurt. Ta-daaa!